I feel really bad but I just didn’t have a great experience here. I’ll start off with the good, the staff was friendly and nice the place did look nice. But that was all.  They had a event going on in the main dining area so they had everyone either sit outside or upstairs. No one sat outside as there wasn’t any heaters and it was cold. We sat up stairs which was basically storageattic. There was stuff on the perimeter partially covered in sheets and 3 tables just shoved up there so extra guests. The attic isn’t closed and we heard the party as we ate. It was also really tight since there was boxes and stuff the tables were squished and wasn’t professional.  I personally think if they had a private event they should have closed the restaurant because you can hear everything and the music was very loud. It felt like we were in a club or bar. I was with my husband for a date night and couldn’t even hear him speak to me. There was even a point where it got extremely awkward because the party were giving speeches and someone started crying. Professionally these events should be held privately where they don’t disrupt the other guests while eating their meals.  The food was okay. It lacked flavor and didn’t really feel authentic to me personally. I love Italian food and while the dishes they had on the menu are indeed made in Italy the flavor profile just wasn’t authentic to me. I’ve had plenty of Italian food and ate in many restaurants and this wasn’t our favorite sadly

Not great. Had a reservation for Valentine’s Day and got seated late. As we were waiting a customer leaving warned us “Dont do it.” We should have taken his advice. As someone who has worked a fair share in hospitality I’m sympathetic to those under duress and in the weeds but this was beyond measure. We had to ask for olive oil four times for stale bread. If it wasn’t already 10pm by the time we got seated we would have walked out. The table next to us sent back both entrees. We were desperately hungry and ate the overly fried calamari and pasta that tasted like it was from a dining hall, but I wouldn’t recommend this restaurant to anyone. I’m perplexed how it received such a high rating.

Terrible service. Had to ask multiple times for a menu, for water, and for bread. Servers came and go asking the same questions but nobody would actually bring anything. 30 minutes after seating and not even the order had been taken. Subpar food too. Lentil soup was not a soup, it was dry, broccoli rabe on the branzino tasted weird, and pappardelle with octopus was sour. For two bad appetizers, two terrible mains and one glass of a cheap chianti the bill was 110 dollars. Oh, and the check took so long to arrive we had to stand up and walk to the exit to get it. The cherry on top was a couple who arrived 25 minutes after us and got drinks and food before us because they knew the owner or manager. Zero stars if I could.

Da Francesco is a quaint Italian restaurant nestled in the heart of Williamsburg, Brooklyn. The cuisine is not only mouthwatering and exquisite but served with such tender love and care. The entire staff works together seamlessly to make each guests experience memorable.  The resturant is more than a place to eat lunch and dinner, its a home away from home with your favorite cousin. The live entertainment merges the guests together in song, dance, and laughter. Francesco himself may bless you with a performance of one of his favorite melodies.  Da Francesco has its own special essence you must experience. Thank me later! 😉

I wanted old Italy. A friend directed me to a friend, who he promised would give me that experience. When I walked in with him, everyone lined up to kiss his hand and pay their respects. Okay, this is exactly what I was looking for. The interior was amazing, and the staff was overwhelmingly friendly. I figured my guide had some influence on that, but still I felt as though I was family in here. Sampled some amazing spirits, and it wasn't until months later I found out who I was hanging out with. Google is an amazing thing. With that being said, I didn't get clipped, and I truly enjoyed the ambiance of Da Francesco. Definitely worth the stop to sample what old Italian America was like years ago.

We came here for dinner for Valentine’s Day and we were not impressed. I made reservations a month in advance and called to make sure they didn’t have a price fix menu. The guy said no and I checked online the day prior to double check I wasn’t missing anything. The restaurant atmosphere was very nice and everyone was wearing red which was cute. We got the menu and it was a very simplified menu. In addition only the wines had prices on them, that too only prices of bottles. I was worried if it was price fix so asked my waiter and he said they “forgot to put the prices on the menu” but he can tell me them. They really didn’t have many choices but we settled for two dishes. We also made sure to request glasses of wine as opposed to bottles (which were the only prices on the menu). Finally our check came and we saw that were a party gratuity on it. Even though we were only a party of two. Overall we spent way too much for food that was sub-par and we were very disappointed with how the restaurant was trying to fool us.

I went here on a Saturday early evening and sat at the bar with one other person. We got a bottle of wine for $25 and a rectangular flatbread-ish pizza for $8. Those two together are a great deal for the price, and before they came we were given very good brick oven bread with a bitter broccoli rabe/olive oil puree dip that was awesome. So if you stop in with another person you can get a substantial snack and half a bottle of wine each for in the vicinity of $20 per person incl. tax & tip. Sweet deal. I ordered a pasta after that which was pretty good, it was gnocchi with brussels sprouts and some other items. I would recommend the pastas, but mainly the reason I am giving this place four stars is due to the aforementioned snack+wine value. The pizza was actually just okay. Atmosphere is that of a warm, dimly lit Italian restaurant, which was pleasant in the cold weather.

A family owned Neapolitan place in the heart of Williamsburg, Brooklyn. Featuring Northern and Southern Italian delicacies at affordable pricing and full bar including wine selection for every palette. Great for a romantic night out, dinner with friends, or just a drink at their beautiful hand carved wooden antique bar.

The food is superb and you will often see the chef, Francesco, and the owner, Carlo, stopping by the tables to say hello. It's a must see in Williamsburg!

Great AUTHENTIC Italian restaurant! Everything is fresh and delicious. The decor is beautiful and original, the mood is perfect for a romantic date or even just grabbing a drink and a bite with friends. It's a hidden gem in Williamsburg but caters equally to the Old Timers and New Comers. It is never overflowing with hipsters and it hasn't given in to the fad that is the hipster eateries as of late. It's a MUST TRY (I recommend the gnocchi).

Service has been a mixed bag over the years, and the menu has expanded and contracted (not sure which is better). But it's still a very charming space, and the Italian standards may not be ground breaking, but won't disappoint.
